                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote scope="sole" xml:id="hand-1">
                                <p>The text was copied in a <term type="script">minuscule</term>
                                    script, in black-brownish ink. The script is slanting to the
                                    right and executed with rapidity. It has few ligatures,
                                    breathings are curved; accents do not join to letters or
                                    breathings, but the circumflex joins the <hi rend="italic">ypsilon</hi>; the <hi rend="italic">iota mutum</hi> is in
                                    use. <hi rend="italic">Alpha</hi>'s loop is open, <hi rend="italic">beta</hi> is small and in a heart-shape, <hi rend="italic">delta</hi> is wide and frequently ligated to a
                                    following iota in a single stroke (e.g. <locus from="3r" to="3r">f. 3r</locus> line 2 ἰδιότης). <hi rend="italic">Tau</hi>
                                    shows the curved shape with no horizontal stroke, usual from
                                    16th century.</p>
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>

                        <additions> A modern hand has added the classmark and "T.27" on the upper
                            margin of f. <locus from="1r" to="1r">1r</locus>.</additions>

